WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified body profile for Hasselblad cameras featuring the Natural
Color Solution (HNCS) and 16‑bit HDR output. It contains the exact
mathematical IDT, the 16‑bit per channel linear encoding model, the
proprietary HDR tone curve parameters with their inverse, native color
space primaries (approximated to ACES AP0 for archival), white balance
presets, sensor metrology data, and the calibration pathway to ACES2065‑1.
This is the single source of truth for linearizing Hasselblad HNCS HDR
stills and video to scene‑referred ACES.

WHY IT EXISTS
HNCS HDR uses pixel‑level calibration and perceptual tone compression to
preserve highlight detail and smooth tonal gradation across over 281 trillion
color combinations. Integrating Hasselblad images into a VFX or ACES pipeline
requires a reversible, auditable IDT. Without this file, users rely on generic
16‑bit to ACES conversions that discard the HNCS perceptual weighting. This
file provides the open, mathematical path back to linear scene light while
respecting the tone curve design.

HOW IT WORKS
Hasselblad outputs linear 16‑bit TIFF (scene‑referred) for ACES workflows,
or an HNCS HDR‑encoded file with a perceptual tone curve.
  Path A (Linear 16‑bit): direct assignment → ACES2065‑1 after white point
    scaling.
  Path B (HNCS HDR): Inverse perceptual tone curve → linear 16‑bit → white
    balance inverse → ACES2065‑1 matrix.
The file also documents sensor metrology (QE, FWC, Dynamic Range) and
the Hasselblad‑specific color calibration profile.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- DaVinci Resolve (via DCTL or OCIO config)
- Nuke (16‑bit EXR / TIFF ingest)
- Baselight (BLG stack)
- Adobe Photoshop / Lightroom (16‑bit linear TIFF export)
- Any ACES‑compliant VFX or DI system.

WHO USES IT
- L2 GIOP Engineers: implement the IDT in pipeline tools.
- L3 GIOP Colorists: verify that the HNCS HDR tone curve is correctly reversed.
- DITs and fine‑art reproduction specialists using Hasselblad for VFX plates.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Replaces the opaque HNCS perceptual compression with an auditable inverse
transform, enabling Hasselblad’s unique color science to be ported exactly
into an ACES‑based compositing environment. Eliminates the risk of double‑
application of the tone curve (once by the camera and once by the ODT).
Provides a certified route from 16‑bit scene‑referred or HNCS HDR to
linear ACES2065‑1.

